

'Very uncomfortable for the Dormouse,' thought Alice;
'only, as it's asleep, I suppose it doesn't mind.'

The table was a large one, but the three were all
sitting on the edge of it, with their legs dangling
into space. 'Hadn't we better all sit in chairs?'
said Alice. 'There's three chairs, but we can only
sit on one of them at once.'

'Not at all,' said the March Hare. 'We may as
well lie down on our backs, and then we can rest our
heads on the arms of the chair.'

  Alice did not quite like the idea of this, but on

  seeing that there was no other way out of it she

  very soon lay down on her back in a large arm-chair.

  The Hatter was just beginning to think that he had

  had quite enough of this, when
